Poland and the cosmos.
Last week, at the meeting of the Ministers of the European Space Agency, Poland was admitted to be the twentieth member of the Agency, it was the second Member State of the former Eastern Block (the Czech Republic became a full member on 12 November 2008).
Poland had started a close collaboration with the ESA in 1994 and during the following years participated in a number of the Agency's projects.
However, the road from Poland to space began much earlier.
Already before the Second World War, passionate Poles were working on space flights; they did not always encounter understanding.
I would like to mention, for example, the conference of A. Šternfeld at the astronomical Observatory in Warsaw, on 6 December 1933, during which he presented ideas drawn from his predecessor's work entitled "Introduction to Astronautry " .
The development of this young engineer (born 1905) left cold listeners, and years later Šternfeld remembered that only Dr. Jan Gadomski was interested in his work.
In 1934, Šternfeld won the Robert Esnault-Pelterie and André Louis Hirsch prize in France for his work "Introduction to the Astronautic".
Dr. Jan Gadomski (1899 - 1966) later became a major propagator of astronomy and astronautry.
He published hundreds of articles in Polish newspapers and wrote many books devoted to this scientific discipline.
Gadomski has become a propagator of world-famous astronautics, and his contribution has been rewarded by the fact that his name has been given to one of the craters of the hidden face of the Moon.
As of 1925, a drain was built in Poland to be equipped with a rocket engine.
Unfortunately, neither the author nor the details of this project are known.
It is also not clear whether the rocket should be used to drive or brake the drain.
The only information known about this draisin is those of the press of the time.
From 1933, the Polish artillery began to devote itself to the rockets.
Research was carried out by the Institut Komórka Techniki Uzbrojenia in collaboration with Professors Mieczyslaw Wolfke and Gustaw Mokrzyckiego.
The documents retained show that this research had reached the test stage.
Of course, with the arrival of the German armies, the research has stopped.
In 1937, the plans of a photoelectric hunting rocket, designed by engineer Rohoziński, appeared in the specialized press and the following year was published the book "Rakieta - torpeda powietrzna i rakietobomba lotnicza" by a writer called Leliwy-Krzywoblocki.
These two projects were designed to use rocket engines in the military.
Just before the war, all rocket technology projects were conducted by the Temporary Scientific Advisory Committee ("Tymczasowy Komitet Doradczo-Naukowy"), which coordinated all the work.
This committee was established in 1937, but after two years of operation, the beginning of the war ended its activities.
After the war, other work on aeronautics was published in the Polish press, thanks to the Polish astronautic society (Polskie Towarzystwo Astronautyczne).
For the first time, there is a company in the November 1954 issue of the Journal Problem, in which are four more detailed articles devoted to aeronautics.
In one of these articles, written by Professor Subotowicze, it is proposed to create a society dedicated to astronautics
At that time, artificial satellite projects had already been launched and it was clear that the field of space research had a future.
At the beginning of 1956, the Polish Astronaut Society (PTA) made efforts to enter the International Astronaut Federation (created in 1951) and from the fall the PTA became a regular member.
The following year, the first president of the PTA, Kazimierz Zarankiewicz (1902 - 1959), became Vice President of the International Astronautical Federation.
He retained his position until his death in 1959.
From 1956, the PTA made a significant contribution to the successful development of the RM meteorological rocket (Rakieta Meteorologiczna), which became the first Polish rocket to carry out scientific research.
The first model, RM-1, was completed in 1957 and the first launch took place on October 10, 1958.
This 1800-metre rocket was 80 cm long and weighed slightly less than 5 kg.
Subsequently, an improved version was built, RM-1A and, during the summer of 1959, two-storey RM-2 rocket flight tests were started in the Bledov desert.
The rocket was 1.4 meters long and probably weighed 11.5 kg.
The following prototype should have been able to carry out concrete scientific work - the RM-34 rocket should have a range of up to 14.5 km and have been used to observe wind in altitude.
But in 1963, all development work was stopped.
The Meteor-1 rocket developed during the period 1962-1965, followed the first RM-type rockets.
The rocket, designed with two floors, had a total length of 510 cm and an initial weight of 32.5 kg.
Three models (named Meteor-1A, -1B and -1C) were developed and distinguished by the dimensions of space reserved for scientific tools.
The Meteor-1A rocket had a volume of 0.4 litres, while in Meteor-1B it was 0.34 litres and in Meteor-1C 0.62 litres.
The maximum reach of all these types of gear was 37 km.
During the period 1965-68, Meteor-2 rockets were developed at the Aeronautical Institute, the first flight tests began in October 1970.
The Meteor-2 rocket had an initial weight of 380 kg and was able to transport a useful load of 10 kg to an altitude of about 60 km.
Subsequently the Meteor-2H and Meteor-3 versions were built.
The entry of Poland to the Committee for Space Research (COSPAR) in 1960 and the establishment of a national COSPAR committee two years later should also be mentioned.
In the context of the Interkosmos programme, Poland also participated in space exploration on artificial Soviet satellites and, in 1978, the pilot Miroslaw Hermaszewski became, after Vladimír Remek, the second non-Soviet cosmonaut of this programme.
