The film Argo: When everything goes bad, call Hollywood.
In November 1979, a crowd of protesters composed of Islamic students attacked the American Embassy of Tehran and hostaged 52 diplomats.
They were to be released in exchange for Shah, Mohammad Reza Pahlavi, who, after the revolution, had fled to the United States, who had supported his regime for decades.
The situation did not offer a positive outcome to the U.S. administration, it could not, in fact, abandon Shah, because it would have severely undermined the trust of its allies in other countries.
However, in Iran, where the revolution had led to the establishment of a theocratic regime, it was unable to obtain the release of hostages.
It was a hard blow for the prestige of the United States, a blow further worsened later by the fiasco of the attempt to release hostages by force.
The sequestrated diplomats were finally released 444 days later, following the negotiations organized by the Algerian Government.
Their fate in the United States caused a wave of solidarity and an anti-iranian feeling.
The Iranian debase greatly contributed to Jimmy Carter's defeat in the 1980 presidential elections against Ronald Reagan.
The film Argo, the actor and director Ben Affleck, describes an episode of this story that offered a small victory to America.
Just before she was occupied, six employees escaped from the embassy.
After complicated outbreaks, they met in the ambassador of Canada's residence.
In collaboration with the Canadian authorities, the CIA succeeded in bringing them out of Iran through a crawling cover: they left the country with Canadian passports as members of a tour team coming to make traces for the shooting of a great science-fiction film.
Combination of genders
The exfiltration expert's plan Tony Mendez required Hollywood's collaboration.
In order to make the legend more credible, specialist stores reported on this film project, press conferences were organized and a fictive production company had real offices.
The details of the operation remained secret for a long time, since the film was based on Tony Mendez's memories.
Affleck's film is an unusual combination of several kinds.
This is part of a political thriller designed realistically but also a "caper film", the story of a successful shot, of a tragedy - such as, for example, in Ocean's eleven, twelve and thirteen trilogy.
The ambiances follow: sequences of Teheran in documentary style (in the subtitled sequences are presented iconic photographs of the era of events and how, thanks to these photos, these same situations have been rewritten in the film, there are no big differences),
lighter passages of Hollywood, treated with irony and a little exaggeration,
And then scenes of the CIA headquarters and other institutions with costumed men discussing the situation around conference tables, in the corridors and on the phone...
Ben Affleck succeeded in relaunching his career in a remarkable way.
As a ridiculized actor, he became a respected performer, and his play of actor ceased to raise ironic remarks.
Argo is his third long film after the dark police " Gone Baby Gone" (2007) and the thriller "The city" (2010).
It is also the first film of Affleck that doesn't take place in its original city, Boston.
The sense of the atmosphere of a place is one of the characteristics that placed its first films above the Hollywood standards.
Affleck also demonstrates this sense of atmosphere in Argo where Teheran's role is "maintained" by Canada.
The best scenes of the film take place in streets, when real facts are rebuilt; the initial sequence of the embassy's fall is impressive by its clarity which also suggests confusion and unpredictability when suddenly, in a given place, a page of history is written.
Affleck and his employees have a similar effect in the fictive scenes (the false painting team in Teheran's basar).
Too many actions in too many places
The director must have been content with a subject offering in fact few palpitating scenes, in the cinematographic sense of the term.
It goes very well, it sometimes adds some elements to reality, and the result is not always as elegant (the scene in which the threat of crisis at Teheran Airport is removed by a phone call in America and the continuation on the landing track is sufficiently drawn by the hair).
The weakness of Argo lies in its discarded character, due to the need to show too many events in too many different places.
If it is true that Alan Arkin and John Goodman are very charming in their role as Hollywood co-operators, their characters would have earned a larger place and they are not, far from there, the only ones in this case.
Affleck's film lacks a bit of dramatic tension, it shows itself with moderate interest, appreciating the achievement and retro style of the 1970s.
He leads the viewer, but with difficulty.
As a reminder of another story, in a certain way, unfinished so far, and as an illustration of the excessive nature of the representation of secret services as omnipotent and omniscient, he does the case.
