Szabo: "The Germans must play a greater role."
Germany chose to abstain in the vote on the admission of the Palestinian State.
According to Stephen Szabo, an expert on relations between the United States and the EU, this decision puts Berlin in a sensitive political situation.
Deutsche Welle: At the beginning of the week, Germany had announced its intention to vote against the request by the Palestinians to obtain observer status from the United Nations.
But then she chose to abstain.
Why?
Stephen Szabo: Germany does not approve of what the Israelis have done in Gaza.
However, Berlin must be careful as it maintains special relations with Israel.
But I also think that it does not support the American position either.
Germany wanted to assert its independence, but not to be too critical to Israel.
During the insurrection in Libya in March 2011, Germany had also chosen to abstain from the vote on the establishment of an air exclusion zone.
Finally, NATO imposed this measure.
Does Germany have difficulties in adopting a clear position on major international issues?
The answer is yes.
The reason for this is that Berlin is revising its foreign policy, seeking to move away from a policy so as to be defined by the Americans and to establish a German foreign policy.
In addition, the lack of coherent and common policy within the Union makes the situation more difficult.
The Germans thus hit several fronts.
They are expected to play a more independent role, but they are not used to it.
I think they are still struggling to find this role, but are on the way to a more "normal" foreign policy.
Foreign policy, such as France or Great Britain
What does the term "normal" of foreign policy mean for the Germans?
It demonstrates the willingness to adopt independent positions from those of the United States and European partners, including with regard to national cases.
I believe that German foreign policy is also determined by its economic policy, therefore by exports and relations with certain regions, such as Russia, China or the Middle East.
The German economic interests are, to a certain extent, different from those of the other major powers, which is why Germany must protect its interests.
Have these economic interests influenced Germany's position with regard to the Middle East conflict and the abstention in the United Nations vote?
Germany first has important opportunities in the Middle East, especially in the Gulf countries.
That is why Berlin must be careful not to strike public opinion, but also the elite of the Arab countries.
This is undoubtedly a crucial element.
However, I would not attach too much importance to this, because this is not a purely unilateral relationship.
But this is in any case a crucial element in the German strategic reflections.
Does Germany abide by its relations with the United States by choosing to abstain in major votes, as in the case of Palestine?
I believe that Europeans and Americans fully understand the German position.
That is why I think the fracture is not so serious as it was in the case of the Libyan question.
Perhaps even Germany will only be more respected.
Germany has thus demonstrated that it must be taken seriously as an international player and that its interests must be taken into account.
In Europe, opinions on the Palestinian initiative are diverse.
On the other hand, the United States has announced its veto with a clear voice.
Do the views differ between the United States and the majority of European countries?
There have always been differences due to the American domestic political scene.
I believe that the Obama Administration secretly demonstrates a great understanding of the European position.
But given the political configuration of the country, the government cannot, of course, defend its position publicly.
I believe that the real differences in opinions are not so large that they always seem to be.
If you observe the relationship between Obama and Israeli Prime Minister Netanyahou, you will note that Obama is far from enthusiastic about Netanyahou's policy.
Does Germany have difficulties in reconciling its close relations with Israel and the United States, on the one hand, with the position of the major European partners, on the other hand?
I don't think it's easy for the Germans.
Of course, it would be a little easier for the Germans if there were a coherent and uniform European policy, but today it is not.
They cannot therefore register within a wider policy line and must affirm their unique position.
That is what they are currently doing in the issue of the euro.
In my view, Germany will take on a locomotive role in the future and will force Europe to adopt a European position.
This is not easy for Germany, especially because of relations with Israel.
This question has always been delicate.
But in my view, the Germans are well aware that they must play a role that marks more their independence.
Does Germany have a role to play as a major player on the international stage, but does Germany only want to play a key role?
Or does it still have difficulties in taking up leading roles?
Germany is still not used to it, it is always uncomfortable and, for obvious reasons, it is still experiencing difficulties in playing a more important role.
Looking, for example, at the euro crisis, it is noted that every time Germany decides to weigh more, many anti-German feelings are heard.
It doesn't make things easier for the Germans.
In fact, this is always the same problem: we do not want to be surrounded by hostile countries.
From this point of view, Germany is in a much more sensitive position than the United States.
It must work with very diverse neighbours and opinions, and this is not easy.
Today, the US's influence on European policy is only decreasing, but at the moment the EU is not filling this vacuum, so what is left?
Germans simply have to play a more important role.
And even if they don't like it, even if it's unpleasant to them and if they're less appreciated, it's life!
Stephen Szabo is the Deputy Director of the Transatlantic Academy in Washington, an institution in which academics and political experts in Europe and North America analyze together the challenges of the transatlantic community.
Szabo is also a member of the German Marshall Fund, where he specializes in German politics, American foreign policy and transatlantic relations.
"Mark protection" in China: when Puma and Armani suddenly become Chinese
Armani and Polo Ralph Lauren are known brands around the world.
Armani Polo... what is this really about?
Behind this name is a trademark officially filed in China, but has nothing to do with the original company.
The trade mark is thus protected by such protection that the company which bears its name cannot file a complaint.
And even if she could, it's not sure that she'd gain cause.
"It is increasingly difficult for foreigners to protect their trademarks in China," explains Thomas Pattloch, lawyer of Taylor Wessing's firm specializing in violation of property rights in the Far East.
Every week, a new file arrives on my desk.
The imitators need only a few additional letters to register their marks.
Thus, instead of Gucci, we recorded Lu-Gucci, and instead of Prada, we recorded Prada-Kny.
German companies are also copied in full legality, such as Puma, the manufacturer of sports products.
Pattloch opens a classer in which records are made at the Beijing Trademark Office.
On September 14, 2010, a Chinese company filed the brand Zegna DF Puma, a name that the company artificially created by owning part of the name Ermenegildo Zegna, the fashion house.
It is known that the Chinese have become world champions of copying and violating intellectual property.
