For four euros, the carriers of the Indonesian volcano are at risk of their lives and health by carrying 70 kilos of sulphur through the scratched stone paths.
There are people for whom work is a hell and others are literally working in hell.
This is the case with Anto Wijaya, one of the 400 minors who earn their lives by carrying the sulphur of the Kawah Ijen volcano, east of the Indonesian island of Java.
It must work every day up to the bottom of the crater, where the sulphuric gas from the earth's interiors solidifies to the contact of the air.
After harvesting large sulphur rocks, which weigh a total of nearly 70 kilos, he installs them in two bamboo baskets that he loads on his shoulders through the stiff paths.
There is only 250 meters to the volcano wing that climbs to 2.386 meters of altitude, but the exhausted carriers spend more than 40 minutes climbing this distance, at a turtle line, keeping the balance and measuring their steps not to stumble and fall into the precipitation.
They know that a false step could cost them life, as it happened to a French tourist who made a mortal fall in the Kawah Ijen volcano several years ago.
Kawah Ijen minors earn 5 cents of euros for each kilo of sulphur extract.
Upstairs, it breaks a path between tourists who photograph them as if they were beasts of circus, and carrying heavy baskets hardly, they walk the 3 kilometers to the balance that a mining company has installed a little downstairs at 1,850 meters of altitude.
This is PT Candi Ngrimbi, a company that has been operating the volcano since 1960 and, as can be said, its employees, to whom it pays 662 Indonesian roupies (5 cents euros) per kilogram of sulphur.
It then sells it to the petrochemical industry at 10,000 roupies (83 cents of euros) as this ore is very present in everyday life and is used to produce candles, fireworks, cosmetics, dynamite and even to wash sugar.
"As we carry about 70 kilos, we earn about 46,000 roupies (3,8 euros) on each trip," explains Anto, who usually travels three times a day.
Each takes 3 hours and ends exhausted, but this allows him to win 138,000 roupies (11,50 euros) at the end of the day.
Although it seems to be a poverty for such an overhuman effort, it is the triple of what it would win in the fields.
"The income of minors is very high here, where the coffee harvest is paid 15,000 roupies (1.20 euros) per day and where the average monthly salary is two million roupies (167 euros)", says the carrier who once worked as a mason on the tourist island of Bali.
There, his salary was 75,000 roupies (6.20 euros) per day and the job was not as difficult, but Anto returned to his family in Banyuwangi, a village near the volcano, for a reason that, in Indonesia, is as indisputable as the sulphur: "I married a young girl from Bali, where they were Hinduists, and I brought her back to Java to convert to Islam."
Anto suffers from asthma, breathes with difficulty, coughs constantly and his eyes are irritated by toxic gases.
