The UNASUR Summit ended without the publication of the Lima Declaration
The VIth Presidential Summit of the Union of South American Nations (Unasur) ended today in Peru without the publication of the Lima Declaration, although it was previously announced and theoretically adopted by the 7 representatives present.
Efe has repeatedly tried to access the document signed at the VIth Regular Meeting of Heads of State and Government of Unasur, but the Ministry of Foreign Affairs and the Presidency initially reported that it would be disclosed after the end of the summit, and then stated that it would be published on the website of the Peruvian Government from time to time.
When they were interviewed on the text, they reported that its content had been presented by the President of Peru, Ollante Humala, in brief statements to the press.
Journalists' access to information on the summit has been constantly limited.
During the day, only the video without the sound of the presidential assembly with the message "private session, limited audio" was broadcast in the press room.
The little information circulated between the journalists was the information provided by the press officers of some of the Unasur governments who attended the meeting, with the exception of the Peruvian spokesman.
The only document published during the day was the list of the presidents present, which caused some discomfort among hundreds of journalists from various national and international media who required more information.
Later, the Peru Presidency sent an e-mail to the media with the "final declaration" of the summit, but it was the speech of President Humala and not the official document that concluded the summit.
In October last, Peru was host of the 3rd summit of the Arab South-Pays America (ASPA) and, on that occasion, although it had been requested by the press in an instance, it had not issued the statement called also the Declaration of Lima, as it had previously been announced.
On the official website of the ASA, it can be verified that the document was published last March.
At both international meetings, the Peruvian authorities have tried to establish secure transmission systems for all journalists, but they have limited information to a maximum.
The summit also concluded with the joint agreement between Chile and Peru to accept a judgment by the Hague Court which sets a different border between the two countries.
The presidents of Peru, Ollanta Humala, and Chile, Sebastián Piñera, met at the regional meeting and said that they would respect the decision of the ICJ to hear the pleas of both parties in the Lima trial against Santiago, which began on Monday in The Hague.
"We will respect and enforce the judgment that will resolve the disputes we are presenting today before this international court," said President Humala, alongside his Chilean counterpart.
"Chile has always been, and will continue to be a country respecting international law, the peaceful resolution of disputes, treaties and international courts," said President Piñera, giving a handful to President Humala, next to the flags of the two countries.
The confirmation by the two presidents that they would submit to the IIC took place after Colombia announced this week the Bogota Covenant by which it had agreed to submit to the decisions of the International Court, following a decision on maritime borders with Nicaragua which it considered to be seriously wrong.
The summit was held without the presence of the presidents of Brazil, Dilma Rouseff, Venezuela, Hugo Chávez, Bolivia, Evo Morales, and Argentina, Cristina Kirchner.
Paraguay, who had suspended Unasur since 2011 after the resignation of its former President Fernando Lugo, did not participate in the meeting.
The host president, Ollanta Humala, was charged with opening the proceedings in the morning and closing the summit in Lima shortly after 12 noon.
The representative read the final document in which he announced that 16 agreements had been adopted and that the 31 project lines of action had been established between South American countries for a total of $17 million in investment.
Among the agreements adopted, he mentioned that UNASUR countries would set up "significant steps to achieve the goal of South American citizenship through the development of agreements on residence permits".
It informed that actions would be undertaken to improve "co-operation in the fight against urban insecurity and international organized crime, actions to improve drug access, low-priced Internet access throughout South America, and to evaluate the risks of natural disasters jointly and effectively".
With a crisis Europe, "the economic consolidation (Latin America) must not have a triumph but must help to increase our productive matrix and maintain a better future for our populations," President Humala concluded.
"We have decided to favour a group of 31 emblematic projects that improve the connection of South America's spaces, especially in rural and border areas... by uniting our countries and generating new economic circuits," said the Peruvian President in a speech.
Among these projects, he mentioned that five were related to Peru and were located on the cross-sectional axes of his territory, from the coast to Brazil, and two were aimed at a more important connection with Ecuador, although he did not give further details.
Similarly, the final document mentions the political situation in Paraguay.
"We hope that the electoral process of this country will allow its reintegration within the Union of the South American Nations," which it is currently excluded.
The need for Latin America to remain a region of prosperity and peace, integrated and having good relations with its neighbours, is another theme addressed at the summit.
In this sense, the Colombian President, Juan Manuel Santos, said, before starting the regional meeting, that he hoped to meet his counterpart from Nicaragua, Daniel Ortega, on the following Saturday in Mexico, to discuss the maritime dispute calmly through a judgement by the CIJ requested by Bogota.
