Hector "Hetin" Reyes "The basketball is my whole life"
The globe-trotter of the basketball "Hetin" Reyes spent more than 60 years of his life in relation to the field and, thanks to him, traveled all over the world.
Few people in Puerto Rico have knowledge of the history of local basketball as big as Hector "Hetin" Reyes.
The reason is that before a brain bleeding sentenced him to a wheelchair in 2008, Reyes was immersed in this sport for more than 60 years, whether as a lower league player, a national basketball team player, manager and leader of the national team, the BSN, with the Vaqueros of Bayamón or as president of the basketball Federation.
"I wore several basketball hats throughout my life, and even several at the same time, like when I was president of the BSN, head of the national team and president of the federation during the 1990s," Reyes remembers during a visit to Primera Hora at his home in Bayamón, where he has lived with Isabel, his faithful wife for more than 50 years.
"The basketball is my whole life."
Reyes doesn't exaggerate when he makes that claim.
The walls of his house, almost all decorated with photos and memories that remind his out of the standard route, bear witness to this.
Bayamón in the heart
From all his memories, those he loves most are those who remind him of his passage as a player in the Vaqueros team in the mid-50s until 1982, after spending 15 years as a co-manager or team manager.
"This was my best years, those I've enjoyed most because I had the chance to participate in eight Vaqueros championships from 1967, whether as manager, co-manager or leader.
This has been many years of satisfaction, including the five contested championships from 1971 to 1975.
I then retired during the championship in 1981, the year when Jerome Mincy entered the BSN team.
From there, "Cuco" Ortiz, who was a great administrator, took the lead of the team," says Reyes.
I remember that Gene Bartow, who had been a leader here and was at the University of Alabama (Birmingham), said to me, "I have a hard player for you, he measures two meters.
Do you want it?"
That's how to start with Mincy, one of the best players in Puerto Rico.
Bartow then recommended me Raymond Gausse, who was naturalized and was one of the best shooters.
I remember he said that if Mincy had allowed Bayamon to win a championship, Gausse would help us try to win another.
He was pleased with the Vaqueros championship with Gausse, but only at distance since in 1988 he was already the great manitou of the federation.
At that time, he preferred to enjoy his duties and Mincy's duties in the national team.
I remember when we won it for the first time in the United States at the pre-Olympic tournament in Mexico in 1989.
Then there was the 1990 World, where we arrived 4th and where we should have won the bronze medal if this Canadian judge had not made us replay the last match, said Reyes.
Is the 1990 World Team the best national team you've ever seen?
She is one of the best, just like the one who beat the Dream Team at the 2004 Olympics.
But my favorite is that of the Pan American Games in Cuba in 1991, when we won gold and we put a raclée to the United States team, which was quite similar to that that won bronze during the World.
This team was not only composed of Mincy, Gausse, Ramon Rivas, Fico López and "Piculín" (Ortiz), but there were also the young (Javier) "Toñito" Colón and James Carter, the brothers León (Francisco and Edgar) and Mario "Quijote" Morales, who had not been able to attend the world of 90 because of a knee problem.
