A course dealing with the "Fin of the World" has just begun
Every week, students explore apocalyptic themes such as nuclear war, zombies, viruses and germs, and climate warming.
This semester, when the professor of religion Stuart Charmé decided to give a course on the end of the world, he knew that he was launching an irresistible hamlet: the end of the Maya calendar, 21 December, to which many people refer as proof of the end of the imminent world.
But Professor Charmé had no idea what was waiting for him in the following months: the catastrophic hurricane Sandy, a tax blow that some called "the Armageddon of Debt" and an increasing conflict involving Israel, the place where Christian theorists at the end of time thought would trigger the apocalypse.
"I didn't realize that this would be the most apocalyptic semester I've ever known," said Professor Charmé this week to his students at the Rutgers-Camden University, New Jersey.
If we analyse what has happened in the world today as if we were 30 days later and that we are devoting it to it, it was a very good period.
And we must remember that what is bad is good for those who believe in apocalypse.
And he is not the only teacher to teach about "the end of the world" this semester, which, in theory, will be the last of history.
In Temple, Deputy Professor Barry Vacker gave the course "Medias, culture and end of the world".
Every week, students explore apocalyptic themes such as nuclear war, zombies, viruses and germs, and climate warming.
"We analyse this because these ideas are proliferating with time," he said, and the way they offer hypothetical scenarios guides a certain human conduct.
If, for example, nuclear weapons fell into the hands of terrorists, a war could break out.
This month, students will analyse films with apocalyptic themes and study how they can be compared with examples of real life.
"I tried to inform my students about what was possible, likely, credible and impossible," Vacker said.
On the main campus of the State University of Pennsylvania, the professor of Latin American History Matthew Restall and his colleague Amara Solari, a deputy professor of Art History and Anthropology, have made a team to give a course, simply entitled "The End of the World".
"We add "2012" to have the opportunity to give the course again, in case the world would not disappear," said Professor Restall.
Despite the imminent disaster, students need to study, create projects and complete their final examinations.
In the state of Pennsylvania, the final examination will be held on the eve of the Apocalypse, which leaves students with no choice but to work "to the same night of the supposed end of the world," said Restall.
The courses proved quite popular.
"It has been complete in two hours," said Restall about his course for high-level students, consisting of 35 students.
We received e-mail messages several weeks before the beginning of the semester, from people who asked if there was still room.
